  "238a02fa-ee6c-4888-b321-7891243f25bf" : {
    "text" : "Service: order-service. Creates customer orders, reserves stock in inventory-service, and emits order.created. System commerce, domain ordering, owner team-ordering. Inbound APIs: POST /api/orders (Create an order and synchronously reserve stock.), GET /api/orders/{id} (Fetch an order by id.). Outbound calls: inventory-service POST /api/inventory/reserve. Produces events: order.created. Consumes events: none. Datastores: db orders, cache plans. Notes: # order-service — narrative Owns the **Order** aggregate (`orders` table). Entry point for the digital, retail, and call-center channels to place an order. ## Business rules - An order is `CREATED`, then `CONFIRMED` once inventory-service confirms the reservation. - If inventory returns `available = false`, the order is **rolled back** and the API returns `409 OUT_OF_STOCK`. Nothing is persisted in that case. ## Integration gotchas - The reservation call is **synchronous and in the same transaction** as the order insert — a slow inventory-service directly affects `POST /api/orders` latency. - `order.created` carries `reservedQty`; consumers (inventory-service) rely on it. Treat the topic schema as a published contract — additive changes only. > Machine-readable detail lives in `catalog-info.yaml`, `openapi.yaml`, `asyncapi.yaml`. > This file is only the \"why\" a human needs.",
